{"questionId":"17630","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company is designing a portable Bluetooth speaker. The speaker is in the&nbsp;shape of a cylinder with a hemisphere at each end of the cylinder.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/dbcd221b4bb4d9c012b7a806f9934266848ede94.png\"></p>\n<p>The dimensions of the speaker, in centimetres, are illustrated in the following diagram where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;is the radius of the hemisphere, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> is the length of the cylinder, with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/d80c74eb2795a9d1751de44a78ed4859ee9616d8.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company has decided that the speaker will have a surface area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>300</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The quality of sound from the speaker will improve as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> increases.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the length of the <strong>cylinder</strong> for which <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> is a maximum.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>150</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></mstyle></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <strong>(M1)</strong> for correct substitution in the given formula for the length of the cylinder.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><mtext>cm</mtext></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)(G2)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)(A1)</strong></em> for correct substitution of the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> sf approximation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>89</mn></math> leading to a correct answer of zero.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17630","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.T_6f","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the length of the cylinder for which V is a maximum.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"f","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.6—Stationary points, local max and min","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}